HEADWORD: Experiential
<hw>Ex*pe`ri*en"tial</hw>
<pr>(⟦ecr⟧ks*p⟦emac⟧`r⟦icr⟧*⟦ecr⟧n"sh⟦ait⟧l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<def>Derived from, or pertaining to, experience.</def>
<rj><au>Coleridge.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is called empirical or <qex>experiential</qex> . . . because it
is given to us by experience or observation, and not obtained as the
result of inference or reasoning.</q> <rj><qau>Sir. W.
Hamilton.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Ex*pe`ri*en"tial*ly</wf>,
<pos>adv.</pos></wordforms> <rj><au>Dr. H. More.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Experientialism</ent>⟦br⟧
